	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Review of supply-side constraints faced under EPAs</h1>

			
			<h4>
												28 February 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> A detailed paper in <i>European Analysis</i> entitled 'Putting liberalisation on the right track - the case of supply-side constraints in the EU-ESA negotiations for an economic partnership agreement' looks at the supply-side constraints faced if EPAs are to support development in the ESA region.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> 'The successful tackling of supply-side constraints is a necessary, but not a sufficient condition to make EPAs work for development' as a range of other factors must also be addressed.</p><p> Key supply-side constraints are identified as:</p>
<ul>

<li>transport infrastructure, which is seen as 'extraordinarily poor' in the ESA region; </li>

<li>telecommunications infrastructure, since it is a key to dynamic adjustment; </li>

<li>inadequate electricity provision in most ESA countries; </li>

<li>the absence of functioning capital markets. The paper recommends 'close cooperation with ongoing World Bank and IMF projects &quot;before market liberalisation to prevent negative effects for development and poverty due to capital market constraints'.</li>

</ul>
<p> While low labour productivity associated with poor education and health-status of workers and low labour-capital ratios in production, is seen as important, the paper argues that 'low labour productivity does not necessarily impede a country's competitiveness', it simply 'shifts a country's comparative advantage to sectors where production is intensive in cheap and unskilled labour'. This gives ESA countries a 'comparative advantage in agricultural products and commodities'. Significantly the paper does not consider low labour productivity to be a supply-side constraint since 'it does not hinder adjustment'. The paper does however recognise 'the negative effects of low labour productivity on the ESA economies', which need to be addressed if 'more sophisticated and capital-intensive production technologies' can be introduced.</p><p> According to the paper 'the main sources of structural market inefficiencies in developing countries are monopolies and lack of economies of scale due to small markets'. It sees liberalisation as an important means of addressing the negative effects of monopolies. However, premature liberalisation would potentially hold back the exploitation, of economies of scale, a particular problem for the manufacturing sector (although not a major problem for the agricultural sector in the ESA region). 'With respect to economies of scale, the crucial point is to make ESA manufacturers fit for competition in time' and allow for infant-industry safeguards. Regional integration through creating larger markets is seen as crucial in generating economies of scale.</p><p> Overall the paper concludes that 'liberalisation is not a magic trick to promote development and that it can only work if many other issues are addressed successfully at the same time'. Unless the supply-side constraints are addressed 'ESA countries run the risk of being worse off after liberalisation than before'. EPAs should include 'conditionality between progress with A-type constraints [supply-side constraints which hinder competitiveness and the capacity to adjust] and further steps of liberalisation', otherwise it may become 'a dangerous experiment in which these people bear the risk'.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.europeananalysis.org.uk/articles/0501-rps1.pdf" target="_self"><i>European Analysis</i> review of EPAs and supply-side constraints in...</a> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The consequence of low labour productivity giving ESA countries a 'comparative advantage in agricultural products and commodities', places agricultural trade issues at centre stage in the EPA negotiations. Issues of the external effects of CAP reform (including the impact of food-safety requirements) and the functioning of commodity markets become critical issues in EPA negotiations. Surprisingly the paper argues that 'low labour productivity does not necessarily impede a country's competitiveness and therefore the outcome of the adjustment process', and since it does not hinder adjustment it is not a supply-side constraint. This rather dismisses what is a major constraint on competitiveness in ACP countries and a major constraint on their ability to adjust to changed economic circumstances, and constitutes a major shortcoming of the analysis. This is a particular issue of concern in the agriculture sector in Africa where numerous studies have shown the profound impact of the HIV/AIDS and malaria pandemics on agricultural productivity and the uptake of new technologies in the agricultural sector.</p><p> It should be noted that the economies-of-scale dimension is becoming an important issue in the agricultural sector given the high fixed costs of SPS compliance. Large volumes are required to spread the unit costs. This could emerge as a serious problem in ESA countries when it comes to exploiting their 'comparative advantage in agricultural products'.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

